<div id="review_3312684162" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3312684162" />
    <a title="Sofia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/114413220-sofia"><img alt="Sofia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607792875p2/114413220.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3312684162?book_show_action=true">May 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sofia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sofia" href="/user/show/114413220-sofia">Sofia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">No one</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Sofia by: </span>
      Grishaverse fans
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=what-a-terrible-ending">what-a-terrible-ending</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=may-december">may-december</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=stock-side-characters">stock-side-characters</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=love-geometry">love-geometry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=lol-what-female-characters">lol-what-female-characters</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=gary-stu">gary-stu</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=disappointments">disappointments</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=strong-female-protagonist">strong-female-protagonist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=failed-romance">failed-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/114413220-sofia?shelf=well-that-was-a-cheap-plot">well-that-was-a-cheap-plot</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3312684162" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9940680200778070310"><b>Why Mal the Malfunction is the Worst Love Interest Ever: An Essay</b><br/><br/><br/>This will be long.<br/>Very long.<br/><b>Also: MILD SPOILERS for <i>Siege and Storm</i> and <i>Shadow and Bone.</i></b><br/><br/><br/><br/>EDIT: The reason I&apos;m writing this review and not Why the Darkling is the Worst Love Interest Ever is because <br/>A. He&apos;s the villain. He&apos;s supposed to be the worst. That&apos;s kind of the point.<br/>B. Mal is supposed to be the hero, but he&apos;s so toxic and awful and I don&apos;t like how he&apos;s portrayed as some ideal man.<br/>C. The Darkling was never really a love inte</span>
  <span id="freeText9940680200778070310" style="display:none"><b>Why Mal the Malfunction is the Worst Love Interest Ever: An Essay</b><br><br><br>This will be long.<br>Very long.<br><b>Also: MILD SPOILERS for <i>Siege and Storm</i> and <i>Shadow and Bone.</i></b><br><br><br><br>EDIT: The reason I'm writing this review and not Why the Darkling is the Worst Love Interest Ever is because <br>A. He's the villain. He's supposed to be the worst. That's kind of the point.<br>B. Mal is supposed to be the hero, but he's so toxic and awful and I don't like how he's portrayed as some ideal man.<br>C. The Darkling was never really a love interest. <br><br><br><br><br><b>1. He’s a possessive piece of trash</b><br><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“Do you? That night at the palace when I saw you on that stage with him, you looked so happy. Like you belonged with him. I can’t get that picture out of my head.”<br><br>“I was happy,” I admitted. “In that moment, I was happy. I’m not like you, Mal. I never really fit in the way that you did. I never really belonged anywhere.”<br><br>“You belonged with me,” he said quietly.</i>
</blockquote><br><br><br>Oooo boy. *deep breaths* I’m already raging mad and I haven’t even started yet. <br><br>Let’s address the problems in this segment. <br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“I was happy.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Alina was happy with the Darkling. She felt like she belonged. But no, Mal says that Alina only belongs with him, because obviously that’s healthy and not at all problematic. <br><br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“I’ve risked my life for you. I’ve walked half the length of Ravka for you, and I’d do it again and again and again just to be with you, just to starve with you and freeze with you and hear you complain about hard cheese every day. So don’t tell me we don’t belong together,” he said fiercely. He was very close now, and my heart was suddenly hammering in my chest. “I’m sorry it took me so long to see you, Alina. But I see you now.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br><br>Can I please just cease to exist?<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“So don’t tell me we don’t belong together.”</i>
</blockquote> <br><br>He kisses her right after this, by the way. <br><br>I’m extremely mad at this paragraph for multiple reasons. One, he doesn’t give Alina a chance to say whether or not she feels the same way. He just assumes that she likes him since he likes her, and he makes the statement that they belong together without actually asking Alina how she feels. <br><br><br>I’m going to skip the part where Mal says he never wants to see her wearing black again (the Darkling’s colors), because <b>that’s just so disgusting and problematic</b> and I honestly don’t have time to digest that right now. <br><br><br>This is just the first book, folks. <br><br>I'm already tired.<br><br><br><b>2. He makes decisions for her</b><br><br><br>Towards the beginning of the second book, Nikolai proposes a political marriage between himself and Alina. He acknowledges that it wouldn’t be a love match, but he knows it’s a smart move, so he waits for Alina’s response.<br><br>Mal never gives her the chance to respond. He physically attacks Nikolai and proceeds to say:<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“You don’t have a right to her.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Oh, so you do? You, Malyen Oretsev, have more of a “right” to Alina than Nikolai does? The logic here is nonexistent. <br><br>Alina tries to calm them down in a rare moment of non-stupidity, but Mal refuses, again, to let her decide for herself, and <b>just assumes that she wouldn’t accept. </b>She’s very hurt by this, understandably. <br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“I don’t need to think about it,” Mal shouted. “And neither does she. It isn’t going to happen.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Again. Let her make her own decisions. She has a brain, even if it’s not a very large one, and she doesn’t need you to decide for her. <br><br><br><br><b>3. He has double standards and is emotionally manipulative</b><br><br><br>REMEMBER THAT TIME HE KISSED ZOYA?<br><br>*uncontrolled laughter* AND THEN HAD THE AUDACITY TO SAY IT WAS ALINA’S FAULT?<br><br><br>THE SAME GUY WHO WOULDN’T EVEN LET ALINA HAVE MALE FRIENDS? <br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“At least she doesn’t flinch when I touch her,” he spat. “You don’t want me, so why do you care if she does?”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>AGAIN, she didn’t flinch because she didn’t want you. She flinched because she literally saw an apparition of the Darkling. And now you’re making out with her enemy just to spite her when she did nothing wrong. <br><br>And <b>he threatens to break up with Alina every time she as much as LOOKS at another man with anything other than hatred.</b><br><br><br><br><b>4. He dislikes the fact that she is more powerful than he is</b><br><br><br>*coughs* *flips Siege and Storm to page 159* Observe.<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>“But when all this is over, Alina, I wonder if you’ll still want me.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>And then he walks out. He just walks out of the room. <br><br>*anger intensifies*<br><br>He does this SO. MUCH. Like every other page. Every interaction with Alina, he’s constantly moaning about how “she doesn’t want me” because “she has powers” and “I’m useless.” <br><br>Do you want her to be weak and rely on you?<br>Is that it?<br><br>(Actually, that <i>is </i>it.)<br><br>Mal is noticeably happier when Alina is weak and not in her power, because then she relies on him. And he’s unhappy when she’s strong and self-confident. <br><br>He’s not letting Alina have her own dreams and ambitions and motivations. He’s constantly making her stressed and depressed by questioning her love for him and <b>saying that because she’s trying to help Ravka, that means she automatically has no time for him.</b><br><br>She’s trying to save an entire country. <br>Calm down.<br>No one cares about you. <br><br>On the contrary, Nikolai encourages Alina to try harder, to be her better self. And he’s not afraid of letting her go. He values her as a free person, unlike Mal. <br><br>Another quote: <br><br><blockquote>
  <i>He let out a bitter bark of laughter. “Do you know how much I want that? To be with you without rank or walls or anything between us? Just to be common again together?” He shook his head. “But you won’t do it, Alina.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>He wants to be common again.<br>Together.<br>He wants Alina to forsake her powers.<br>To give up Ravka and just live with him and bE A STUPID PEASANT IN THE COUNTRYSIDE WITH NO RESPONSIBILITY JUST BECAUSE HE WANTS THAT. <br><br><blockquote>
  <i>"I wasn’t afraid of you, Alina. I was afraid of losing you. The girl you were becoming didn’t need me anymore, but she’s who you were always meant to be.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Nononono wait a second- <br>*crying* <br>*crying abruptly stops*<br><br>Okay, I’m good. <br>I find this extremely hilarious and extremely sad at the same time. <br><br>He doesn’t like Alina with powers because she’s confident, strong, and brave.<br><b>He likes weak, insecure Alina better because that version of Alina made him feel like a big, tough man.</b><br><br>He’s continually insecure that Alina will leave him simply because she doesn’t need him. He doesn’t want her to become a more independent, strong person. <br><br><br><br><br><b>5. He shows signs of potentially becoming physically abusive</b><br><br><br>Mal has a problem with “curling his fingers into fists” whenever Alina shows ANY sign of not wanting to make out right at that moment. And then he assumes she’s thinking about another guy. <br><br>And then, after that, he doesn’t give her any chance to explain. <br><br>I’m so done with this.<br><br>He shows every sign of becoming physically abusive. The fists, the possessiveness, the jealousy. <br><br>There’s this one line that I couldn’t find in the book that was a perfect example. He kisses her, she stiffens noticeably because she literally has a hallucination of the Darkling standing behind him. He assumes she doesn’t love him anymore and storms out with his hands curled into fists. <br><br>You have to give her some space.<br><br>The problem with Mal is that he constantly decides that HE knows better. He knows everything Alina is thinking. He can make decisions for her. And then he makes her feel like trash and leaves it all up to her to “fix” their relationship. Which he broke, by the way, by not letting her speak and just assuming he knew what she meant. <br><br><br><br><b>6. He doesn’t allow her to have male friends</b><br><br><br>I’m going to share a quote with you that actually made me laugh out loud:<br><br><blockquote>
  <i>Mal shook his head in disgust. “I let him push me away. The meetings, the council sessions, the dinners. I let him edge me out. Just waiting, hoping that you’d miss me enough to tell them all to go to hell.”</i>
</blockquote><br><br>*wheezing* So he’s saying that Alina can’t have male friends? That she actually has to tell Nikolai to go to hell just because Mal is so jealous that he can’t stomach the idea of Alina having a life? <br><br>I should stop laughing and start crying. <br><br>I’m not going to paste the infamous flinching quote in here again, but the same points apply. He assumed that Alina was thinking about another guy, and instead of asking her if she was, <b>he gets angry and guilt-trips her, making her think it’s all her fault. </b><br><br>I believe this is called gaslighting. <br><br><br><br><br><b>TL;DR, Mal is a needy, insecure, jealous, possessive, toxic, abusive excuse for a human being. </b><br><br><br>Me @ Mal:<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1612279216i/30800496._SX540_.png" alt="Trash Opinion GIF - Trash Opinion SplishSplash - Discover &amp; Share GIFs" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>______<br><br><br>1. Mal. Please die.<br>2. Alina just doomed the whole Ravka because she was too busy professing her love to Mal and wouldn't kill a stupid deer.<br><br><br>I believe there is one fundamental problem with <i>Shadow and Bone.</i> Actually, that's not true. There are many, many problems, but one irked me the most (I'm not counting Mal, my mortal enemy). <br><br><br>You can't count on me to root for the "good guys" just because I'm supposed to. I will come into a book with absolutely no opinions whatsoever (excluding The Cruel Prince, which I was in love with before I even started) and form my own idea as to which side I should like more. The Darkling was just so much better than Mal and Alina. And I don't even like the Darkling. He's an annoying jerk with no clear motive and I kind of hate him, but guess what? I hate Alina and Mal even more. Fun times. <br><br><br>Sometimes I feel like authors expect me to side with the morally good people as a principle, but I don't care if you're a good person or not. I just want you to be somewhat interesting. Mal and Alina were as interesting as this piece of white bread: <br><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1607458236i/30492907._SX540_.jpg" alt="Who Made That Sliced Bread? - The New York Times" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>Only I would rather spend a day with a slice of bread than with Malyen Oretsev. <br><br><br>This book suffers from a serious case of not like other girls™. Alina Starkov(a) is the only female character in this entire novel that isn't a gossipy, appearance-obsessed, "shallow" person, but she's more shallow than all of them because she's bringing them down while putting herself up, and that makes me automatically hate her. <br><br><br>Take Zoya, for example, who had the potential for an awesome redemption arc but instead tried to kill Alina for having stronger powers. Because ✨logic.✨ The characters all fit into traditional roles:<br><br>Mal: The love interest who would do anything for the protagonist<br>Alina: The speshul protagonist with speshul powers who has a destiny she never dreamed of<br>Zoya: The mean girl who exists only to make life a living hell for the protagonist <br>The Darkling: Basically Kylo Ren, but worse<br><br><br>Alina is the definition of a Mary Sue. She starts off incompetent and idiotic, and ends the book suddenly a goddess and idiotic. I guess it was too much to ask for character development.<br><br><br><br>Moving on to Mal, who may be The Worst Character Of All Time for the reasons listed below.<br><br><br><b>1. He's a jealous jerk.</b><br>I'm thinking of that time when he threatened to break off his friendship with Alina because he thought she was in a relationship with the Darkling. Learn what the word "no" means, you insufferable moldy waffle. And he's supposed to be "noble." Look up <i>feminism</i> and only come back here when you've written a 10-page essay on why you are a terrible person. <br><br><br><b>2. He uses Alina for his own wants.</b><br>He constantly complains about how "she's different" since she got powers and he's "worried that she doesn't love me anymore." *sigh* There is so much that's wrong with... *gestures vaguely* you. First of all, stop moping because "she might not love" you. Hasn't she sacrificed everything for you? Just because she wants to fight for the good of all Ravka doesn't mean you have the right to be a jerk about that because you want more time with her. In case you didn't already know, Alina is a person too and has stuff she needs to get done. You're just making things worse, you clingy spoiled octopus. <br><br><br><br>Anyway, this was terrible. It's basically all the YA tropes shoved into a bowl and halfheartedly mixed for a few seconds. <br><br><br>1.5 stars, because I laughed during all the dark moments</span>
  <a data-text-id="9940680200778070310" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


